            $(function () {
        try {
            //ParentBanner
            const aParentTags = document.querySelectorAll('#Portals_swiper a');

                if (banner.TransactionNumber) {
                    map.set(banner.TransactionNumber.toString(), banner);
                }
                return map;
            }, new Map());
            aParentTags.forEach(aParentTag => {
                const transId = aParentTag.id.split('_').pop()
                const bannerData = parentBannerMap.get(transId);
                if (bannerData) {
                    aParentTag.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
                        window?.__ga_push({
                            'event': 'legacy_click',
                            'legacy_element_value': "header-topbar-" + bannerData.Title
                        });
                    });
                }
            });
    
            //SubBanner
            const subBanners = __initialState__?.__ServiceDataAllBanner?.flatMap(banner => banner?.ChildBannerInfo)?.filter(Boolean);
            if (subBanners?.length > 0) {
                let impressionArry = [];
                const subBannerMap = subBanners.reduce((map, banner) => {
                    if (banner.TransactionNumber) {
                        map.set(banner.TransactionNumber.toString(), banner);
                    }
                    return map;
                }, new Map());
    
                const observer = new MutationObserver((mutationsList) => {
                    for (let mutation of mutationsList) {
                        if (mutation.type === 'childList') {
                            mutation.addedNodes.forEach(node => {
                                if (node.id === 'popover-header-portal') {
                                    const aTags = node.querySelectorAll('a');
                                    aTags.forEach(aTag => {
                                        const transId = aTag.id.split('_').pop()

                                        if (bannerData) {
                                            const isImpressioned = impressionArry.includes(transId);
                                            if (!isImpressioned) {
                                                impressionArry.push(transId);
                                                window?.__ga_push({
                                                    'event': 'legacy_view',
                                                    'legacy_element_value': "header-topbar-" + bannerData.Title
                                                });
                                            }
                                            if (!aTag.hasAttribute('data-click-bound')) {

                                                        'event': 'legacy_click',
                                                        'legacy_element_value': "header-topbar-" + bannerData.Title
                                                    });
                                                });
                                            }
                                        }
                                    });
                                }
                            });
                        }
                    }
                });
                observer.observe(document.body, { childList: true });
            }
        } catch (error) {
            console.error(error);

What does that mean in practical terms? When you enter a command into a program, be it via mouse click, button push, or typed phrase, the CPU converts that command into language that the other components recognize and to which they respond. \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are two dominant manufacturers of the x86 processors used in desktop computing. Nothing will function if a processor doesn’t sit properly in the motherboard and if the motherboard is not designed for it. AMD CPUs must fit into AMD motherboards and Intel CPUs in Intel motherboards. Certain CPUs fit specific motherboard socket types and chipsets as well. Check product information pages for compatibility; see the \u003Ca class='link-more' href='https:\u002F\u002Fwww.newegg.com\u002Finsider\u002Fhow-to-choose-a-motherboard\u002F'\u003E\u003Cspan\u003Emotherboard buying guide\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E for more guidance.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManufacturers have developed safeguards against mixing incorrect parts. However—if a CPU isn’t suitable for the motherboard you chose, it literally will not fit— the chip has a pin configuration that is different from the one in the board's CPU socket. If you use a tool like the Newegg PC Builder or buy a combo package on Newegg.com, then Newegg double-checks to ensure that the motherboard and CPU you purchased are compatible. Still, it's wise to double-check online and consult your user manuals to ensure all components match before starting.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESome motherboards have extra bells and whistles, such as overclocking your CPU or adding additional lighting features. RAM modules fit into the DIMM slots on a motherboard.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe amount and type of desktop RAM you install in your system directly affects system performance. 16-32 GB of RAM is usually enough for a modern \u003Ca class='link-more' href='https:\u002F\u002Fwww.newegg{0}\u002FGaming-Desktops\u002FSubCategory\u002FID-3742'\u003E\u003Cspan\u003Egaming desktop\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Nvidia and AMD are the industry leaders for the graphics processing chips (GPUs) onboard graphics cards. A \u003Ca class='link-more' href='https:\u002F\u002Fwww.newegg{0}\u002FSSDs\u002FCategory\u002FID-119'\u003E\u003Cspan\u003Esolid-state drive\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, or SSD, stores all its data in integrated circuits. SSDs are often much faster and quieter than HDDs, and they are less likely to break because they don’t rely on mechanical operations to function. However, SSDs are more expensive than HDDs, and you’ll expect to pay more per gigabyte of storage for the more advanced drives.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn SSD is commonly used as a primary drive to hold your operating system and other frequently used and essential applications, in tandem with a high-capacity HDD that holds larger media files.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHDDs and 2.5-inch SSDs connect to the motherboard using a SATAIII connection. Without a PSU, your PC couldn’t do anything other than sit there and look pretty. The PSU does more than act as a hub for incoming power, too—one of the PSU’s primary functions is to transform the power coming out of your wall outlet into a form usable by the system’s many components, all of which have different wattage and voltage requirements.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHow much wattage your system requires depends on the components that you choose. If you’re a first-time PC builder and you’re looking to find the right PC cooling solution for your new rig, then you’ll want to consider the benefits and drawbacks of each type of cooling carefully.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAir cooling for PCs is standard; you can’t get much simpler than a \u003Ca class='link-more' href='https:\u002F\u002Fwww.newegg{0}\u002FCPU-Fans-Heatsinks\u002FSubCategory\u002FID-574'\u003E\u003Cspan\u003Eheat sink and fan\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Plug the case fans in, mount the heat sink on the CPU with a few screws, and then your heat and sink fan is complete. If you don’t plan on overclocking your PC, then an air-cooled CPU heatsink will be sufficient.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf you like to push the limits by overclocking your components, we recommend water cooling your customized PC. Pre-built water cooling kits (called All-in-Ones or AiO water cooling) are the best option for beginners because you only need to mount them. There are no worries about filling and building. Simply mount the radiator and block inside your PC, and you’re on your way.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor experienced builders, a \u003Ca class='link-more' href='https:\u002F\u002Fwww.newegg{0}\u002Fp\u002Fpl?N=100074981%20600036012'\u003E\u003Cspan\u003EDIY water cooling kit\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E with individual parts offers more flexibility. A typical DIY water cooling kit consists of a radiator, hoses, pump, water block, reservoir, and fan. When these pieces are installed and working together, they are called a loop and are very similar to what you would find under the hood of your car.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},{"question":"Do you need a Battery Backup (UPS) when building a custom PC?","answerHtml":"\u003Cp\u003EYes, adding a \u003Ca class='link-more' href='https:\u002F\u002Fwww.newegg.com\u002FBattery-Backup-UPS\u002FSubCategory\u002FID-72'\u003E\u003Cspan\u003EBattery Backup (UPS)\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E is a smart decision when building a custom PC, especially if you rely on your system for gaming, work, or critical tasks. A UPS provides backup power during outages, ensuring that your system doesn't shut down unexpectedly, preventing data loss and potential damage to hardware. It also protects against power surges and fluctuations, which can harm sensitive components like your motherboard and GPU.
